DID YOU KNOW..that in 1893 Dr. Daniel Hale Williams was the first person to conduct a successful open-heart surgery IN HISTORY?! AND...Dr. Williams was not just an innovative and skilled surgeon, he was also America’s FIRST BLACK cardiologist. Whoa that’s amazing! Many people don’t know about that.

The truth? African Americans face a much higher risk of heart disease than any other demographic in America. So it’s important to remember that while we are honoring our history this month, we must also honor your bodies.

With a fresh, healthy diet of whole foods, regular exercise, and building our inner strength, we can reduce the risk of heart disease and avoid experiencing Dr. Williams’ life-saving procedure.

Between bullying, road rage, pandemic, and mass shootings the message is CLEAR! We all need to slow down, open our eyes to see those who need help then get it for them, and open our minds to an awareness far beyond what we have been used to doing. 

It’s not too late! Tough times are just a test of character. It can make you stronger and you CAN be, just don’t give up!

Need assistance? Talk to someone. Don’t suffer in silence until it’s too late. Taking your own life is like the devil grabbing you by the throat. 

Never mistake the fact that you were born to win! You are a gem and there are people on this Earth that care about you and your well-being. Don’t ruin it! Talk to me.

Now is the time to “Take Back Your Life!”

Now is the time to take control of your health!

●Support a woman-owned business

●	Show gratitude to the amazing women in your life by saying thank you

●Tightness in your chest
●	Shortness of breath

PLEASE…call your doctor immediately and get screened for heart disease.

- Limit your alcohol consumption
- Try for about 50 minutes of exercise three times a week
- Practice relaxation techniques in order to reduce stress

Be mindful, pace yourself, and remember to enjoy the small things.

Here are my 5 top tips to maintain your figure during the holidays:

2. Choose the healthiest holiday food options, like snacking on the veggie tray instead of the cookie tray.

3. Add extra protein and fiber to your daily diet to balance out the empty carbohydrates from holiday sweets.

4. Kick up the exercise on the days you overindulge to keep the extra calories from adding up.
